          "body": "The Chronicler (writing after 539 BC for the returned exiles) does not tell this story to satisfy historical curiosity. His community has no Davidic king, a rebuilt but modest second temple, and a political situation of Persian vassalage. The question haunting every reader is: did the exile cancel the covenant? The chapter's answer is built into the oracle's repeated 'forever': the throne of David's son will be established forever (17:12, 14); the blessing is forever (17:27). No human event — not Babylon, not the end of the monarchy — can revoke what God has covenanted. As Eugene Merrill argues in his commentary on Chronicles (1 Chron., NAC), the Chronicler presents the Davidic covenant as the theological anchor of post-exilic hope precisely because it was unconditional in its ultimate provision. The Son whose throne would be established forever had not yet come when Ezra read the law or when Nehemiah rebuilt the wall. The covenant was still outstanding. For the Chronicler's first readers, as for the church reading this text in the period between Pentecost and the Parousia, the chapter's posture is the one David models: sit before the LORD, rehearse the word He has spoken, ask Him to do what He said, and declare that what He has blessed is blessed forever."
